### **3. Two people get on the same lift on the ground floor. First person goes to 40/F. Assuming the second person does not go to the same (40/F) floor, what is the minimum time it will take for the lift to get to 40/F if it has to stop at another floor between 1/F and 40/F?**

#### Step 1: Minimum time condition
To minimize the total time, the elevator should stop at the highest possible floor before reaching the 40th floor. This ensures that the elevator spends as little time as possible decelerating and accelerating at intermediate stops.

#### Step 2: Stop at the 39th floor
The elevator stops at the 39th floor, which is the highest floor below the 40th floor. The height of the 39th floor is:
$$
\text{Height of 39/F} = 39 \times 5 = 195 \, \text{meters}.
$$

#### Step 3: Time to reach the 39th floor
Using the same method as in Question 1, the total time to reach the 39th floor is:
$$
t_{\text{39/F}} = 45 \, \text{seconds}.
$$

#### Step 4: Deceleration from 39/F to 40/F
The elevator decelerates from $5 \, \text{m/s}$ to rest over the last 5 meters (height of the 40th floor). The time to decelerate is:
$$
t_{\text{decel}} = \frac{\text{distance}}{\text{average velocity}} = \frac{5}{\frac{5 + 0}{2}} = 5 \, \text{seconds}.
$$

#### Step 5: Total time to reach the 40th floor
The total time is the sum of the time to reach the 39th floor and the time to decelerate to the 40th floor:
$$
t_{\text{total}} = t_{\text{39/F}} + t_{\text{decel}} = 45 + 5 = 50 \, \text{seconds}.
$$

**Answer to Question 3:**
$$
\boxed{50 \, \text{seconds}}
$$
